data: {"type":"result","content":"LITERATURE REVIEW OUTLINE\nBackground: Acute Myeloid Leukemia (AML) exhibits significant biological and clinical heterogeneity, necessitating precise risk stratification to guide therapeutic decisions. Over the past 15 years, the integration of cytogenetics, somatic mutations, and minimal residual disease (MRD) has transformed prognostic models, most notably through the European LeukemiaNet (ELN) 2022 classification. Despite advances, challenges persist in risk prediction for intermediate-risk patients and those with rare or complex mutational profiles, highlighting the need for refined, dynamic, and integrative prognostic tools.\n\nDETAILED SECTIONS:\n\n1. Introduction and Clinical Context of AML Risk Stratification\nDescription: Introduce AML as a heterogeneous disease and the importance of risk-adapted therapy. Outline the historical evolution of risk classification systems, from cytogenetics-based models to modern molecularly integrated frameworks. Define key concepts such as ELN risk categories, MRD, and personalized prognostication, and state the objectives and scope of the review.\n\n2. Methods and Search Strategy\nDescription: Detail the systematic approach to literature selection, including databases searched (e.g., PubMed, Scopus), inclusion/exclusion criteria (e.g., peer-reviewed studies, 2008–2023, focus on prospective trials and large cohorts), keywords used (e.g., AML, risk stratification, ELN, MRD, FLT3, NPM1), and quality assessment methods for evidence synthesis.\n\n3. Current State of Molecular and Cytogenetic Risk Classification\nDescription: Synthesize evidence on the prognostic impact of established and emerging genetic markers (e.g., FLT3-ITD, NPM1, biallelic CEBPA, TP53, IDH1/2) and their incorporation into systems like ELN 2022. Discuss the challenges of co-mutation patterns, clonal heterogeneity, and variant interpretation in risk assignment, particularly in intermediate-risk AML.\n\n4. Dynamic Risk Assessment: The Role of Minimal Residual Disease\nDescription: Evaluate the clinical utility of MRD monitoring via multiparameter flow cytometry and NGS in predicting relapse and survival. Review data from major clinical trials demonstrating how MRD status influences post-remission therapy decisions and outcomes, and discuss standardization challenges and timing of assessment.\n\n5. Emerging Approaches: Multi-Omics and Machine Learning in Prognostic Modeling\nDescription: Explore the potential of integrated omics (genomics, transcriptomics, epigenomics) and artificial intelligence to improve risk prediction. Highlight studies applying machine learning to large-scale datasets for identifying novel risk signatures and personalizing outcome forecasts beyond conventional stratification.\n\n6. Conclusions and Future Directions\nDescription: Summarize key advances and persistent gaps in AML risk stratification. Address unresolved controversies, such as the weighting of co-mutations and MRD integration into formal risk categories. Propose future research priorities, including prospective validation of novel models, standardization of biomarker assays, and equitable implementation of precision prognostication in clinical practice.\n\n"}

