data: {"type":"result","content":"\n\n## 4. Dynamic Risk Assessment: The Role of Minimal Residual Disease\n\n### 4.1 MRD Detection Technol"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ogies\n\nMinimal residual disease (MRD) detection has emerged as a critical component in the managemen"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"t of acute myeloid leukemia (AML), providing deeper insights into treatment response beyond conventi"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"onal morphologic assessment. MRD refers to the presence of leukemic cells below the threshold of det"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ection by standard cytomorphologic methods (typically 5% blasts) and represents a powerful tool for "}

data: {"type":"result","content":"dynamic risk assessment. This section compares the primary methodologies employed for MRD detection "}

data: {"type":"result","content":"in AML, focusing on multiparameter flow cytometry (MFC) and next-generation sequencing (NGS) approac"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"hes.\n\nMultiparameter flow cytometry relies on the identification of leukemia-associated immunophenot"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ypes (LAIPs) that differ from normal hematopoietic cells. These aberrant phenotypes may include asyn"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"chronous antigen expression, over-expression or under-expression of antigens, or abnormal combinatio"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ns of antigens not found on normal myeloid progenitors. Modern flow cytometry platforms utilize 8-10"}

data: {"type":"result","content":" colors simultaneously, allowing for detailed immunophenotypic characterization and improved discrim"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ination between malignant and normal cells.\n\nIn contrast, NGS-based MRD detection focuses on identif"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ying specific genetic alterations present in leukemic cells. This approach includes targeted sequenc"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ing of recurrent mutations (such as NPM1, FLT3, IDH1/2) and detection of unique patient-specific seq"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"uences. NGS offers the advantage of molecular specificity and potentially higher sensitivity compare"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"d to MFC, particularly for certain genetic lesions.\n\nEach methodology carries distinct advantages an"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"d limitations that impact clinical utility. MFC provides rapid results with relatively broad applica"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"bility across AML subtypes but requires specialized expertise for analysis and standardization. NGS "}

data: {"type":"result","content":"offers exceptional sensitivity for tracking specific molecular markers but involves longer turnaroun"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"d times and higher costs. The selection between these methods often depends on institutional resourc"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"es, the specific clinical context, and the molecular profile of the individual patient's disease.\n\n#"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"### Comparative Analysis of MRD Detection Technologies\n\nThe sensitivity of MRD detection techniques "}

data: {"type":"result","content":"represents a critical parameter for clinical decision-making. MFC typically achieves sensitivity in "}

data: {"type":"result","content":"the range of 10^-3 to 10^-4 (one leukemic cell among 1,000-10,000 normal cells), while NGS-based met"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"hods can reach sensitivities of 10^-4 to 10^-6, depending on sequencing depth and the specific targe"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"t. This enhanced sensitivity of NGS becomes particularly relevant when attempting to identify patien"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ts with very low-level disease who remain at risk for relapse.\n\nSpecificity also differs between met"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"hodologies. NGS provides excellent specificity when tracking defined mutations, though challenges ex"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ist in distinguishing between residual leukemia and clonal hematopoiesis of indeterminate potential "}

data: {"type":"result","content":"(CHIP). MFC specificity relies heavily on the stability of leukemia-associated immunophenotypes, whi"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ch may shift during therapy or disease evolution.\n\nImplementation feasibility represents another imp"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"ortant consideration. MFC offers relatively rapid turnaround times (typically 1-2 days) and is widel"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"y available at major treatment centers. NGS typically requires more specialized infrastructure, bioi"}

data: {"type":"result","content":"nformatics support, and longer processing times (7-14 days), which may limit its applicability in ti"}

